Comparación de Modelos con teoría de la información¶

Jaccard similarity coefficient¶

Measures the similarity of label sets $y_l$ and $\hat{y}_l$ (in set of sets representation).

The coefficient for each label $l$ is $$J_l = J(y_l, \hat{y}_l) = \frac{|y_l\cap \hat{y}_l|}{|y_l\cup \hat{y}_l|}$$

Example $$ y = (1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 4, 4, 4, 4) $$ $$ \hat{y} = (1, 1, 1, 1, 2, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4)$$

$$ J_1 = J(y_1, \hat{y}_1) = \frac{1}{4}$$

Jaccard coefficient-Macro: $$\frac{1}{M} \sum_{l=1}^M J(y_l, \hat{y}_l)$$

Jaccard coefficient-Weighted: $$\frac{1}{N}\sum_{l=1}^M |y_l| J(y_l, \hat{y}_l)$$

Hamming loss function¶

In information theory, the Hamming distance is defined as the number of positions at which two strings or vectors of the same length differ. Essentially, it quantifies the minimum number of substitutions needed to transform one string into the other.

$$ L_{hamming}(y, \hat{y}) = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N 1(y_i \neq \hat{y}_i)$$

Example $$ y = (1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 4, 4, 4, 4) $$ $$ \hat{y} = (1, 1, 1, 1, 2, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4)$$

$$ L_{hamming}(y, \hat{y}) = \frac{2}{10}$$

Joint Distribution¶

The joint distribution of two random variables 𝑋 X and 𝑌 Y describes how they occur together.

$$p(l, l') = P(l \cap l') = \frac{|y_l \cap y_{l'}|}{N}$$
$$ p(Y, \hat{Y} ) = \frac{1}{N} M_c $$
$$ p(Y, \hat{Y} ) = \begin{bmatrix} .1 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ .2 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ .1 & .2 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & .1 & .2 & .1 \end{bmatrix} $$
$$ p(Y, \hat{Y} ) = \begin{bmatrix} .1 & 0 & 0 & 0 & | & .1 \\ .2 & 0 & 0 & 0 & | & .2 \\ .1 & .2 & 0 & 0 & | & .3 \\ 0 & .1 & .2 & .1 & | & .4 \\ \hline .4 & .3 & .2 & .1 & | & 1 \end{bmatrix} $$

Entropy¶

Entropy is a measure of uncertainty or disorder in a dataset. It tells us how unpredictable or mixed the data is.

$$ \Eta (X) = \sum_{x \in X} p(x) \log_2 \frac{1}{p(x)}= -\sum_{x \in X} p(x) \log_2 p(x)$$

Donde $p(x) := \mathbb{P}[X = x]$

$$ \Eta (X) = \sum_{i=1}^m \mathbb{P}(X = i) \log_2 \frac{1}{\mathbb{P}(X = i)}= -\sum_{i=1}^m \mathbb{P}(X = i) \log_2 \mathbb{P}(X = i)$$
$$Y = (1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 4, 4, 4, 4)$$$$ \Eta (Y) =\frac{1}{10}\log_2\frac{10}{1} +\frac{2}{10}\log_2\frac{10}{2} +\frac{3}{10}\log_2\frac{10}{3} +\frac{4}{10}\log_2\frac{10}{4} = 1.85 \ \text{bits}$$

Mutual Information¶

Mutual information measures how much knowing one variable reduces uncertainty about another. It’s like asking, "How much does knowing $X$ help me predict $Y$?"

Example:

  • If $X$ = “amount of study” and $Y$ = “exam score,” a high mutual information means studying strongly affects the score.
  • If $X$ = “eye color” and $Y$ = “exam score,” mutual information is close to zero (they are unrelated).

Use:

  • Feature selection (choosing the most relevant variables)
  • Clustering (finding dependent structures in data)
  • Deep learning (regularization techniques using MI)
$$I(X, Y) = \sum_{x \in \mathcal{X}, y \in \mathcal{y} }p(x,y) \log_2 \frac{p(x,y)}{p(x) p(y)}$$

where $p(x, y) = p_{X,Y}(x,y) := \mathbb{P}[X = x, Y = y]$ and $p(y) = p_{Y}(y) = \mathbb{P}[Y = y]$.

$$ p(Y, \hat{Y}) = \begin{bmatrix} .1 & 0 & 0 & 0 & | & .1 \\ .2 & 0 & 0 & 0 & | & .2 \\ .1 & .2 & 0 & 0 & | & .3 \\ 0 & .1 & .2 & .1 & | & .4 \\ \hline .4 & .3 & .2 & .1 & | & 1 \end{bmatrix} $$
$$ I(Y, \hat{Y}) = 0.1 \log_2 \frac{0.1}{0.1 \cdot 0.4} + 0.2 \log_2 \frac{0.2}{0.2 \cdot 0.4} + 0.1 \log_2 \frac{0.1}{0.3 \cdot 0.4} + 0.2 \log_2 \frac{0.2}{0.3 \cdot 0.3} + 0.1 \log_2 \frac{0.1}{0.3 \cdot 0.3} + 0.2 \log_2 \frac{0.2}{0.4 \cdot 0.2} + 0.1 \log_2 \frac{0.1}{0.4 \cdot 0.1} $$
$$I(X, Y) = \mathrm{H} (Y) - \mathrm{H} (Y|X) = \mathrm{H} (X) - \mathrm{H} (X|Y)$$

Cuando una columna es siempre igual, la informacion mutua es 0.
Cuando cambian igual (o completamente diferente) es algo cerca de 0.5

Bayes' Theorem¶

Bayes' theorem updates our belief about an event given new evidence.

$$ P(A|B) = \frac{P(A \cap B)}{P(B)} = \frac{P(A,B)}{P(B)} = \frac{P(B|A) P(A)}{P(B)} $$

Conditional Entropy¶

This measures the remaining uncertainty in $Y$ after knowing $X$.

Example:

  • If $X$ = "weather" and $Y$ = "umbrella usage,"
    • If weather perfectly determines umbrella use, $H(Y | X) = 0$ (no uncertainty left).
    • If people randomly choose to carry umbrellas, $H(Y | X)$ is high (still uncertain).

Use:

  • Decision trees (choosing splits based on entropy reduction)
  • Information theory (data compression, signal processing)

One may also define the conditional entropy of two variables $X$ and $Y$ taking values from sets $\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{Y}$ respectively, as:

$$ \mathrm{H}(X|Y) = -\sum_{x,y \in \mathcal{X} \times \mathcal{Y}} p(x,y) \log \frac{p(x,y)}{p(y)}, $$
$$\mathrm{H}(X|Y) = \mathrm{H}(X) -I(X,Y)$$
$$ p(Y, \hat{Y}) = \begin{bmatrix} .1 & 0 & 0 & 0 & | & .1 \\ .2 & 0 & 0 & 0 & | & .2 \\ .1 & .2 & 0 & 0 & | & .3 \\ 0 & .1 & .2 & .1 & | & .4 \\ \hline .4 & .3 & .2 & .1 & | & 1 \end{bmatrix} $$
$$ - \mathrm{H}(Y|\hat{Y}) = 0.1 \log_2 \frac{0.1}{0.4} + 0.2 \log_2 \frac{0.2}{0.4} + 0.1 \log_2 \frac{0.1}{0.4} + 0.2 \log_2 \frac{0.2}{0.3} + 0.1 \log_2 \frac{0.1}{0.3} + 0.2 \log_2 \frac{0.2}{0.2} + 0.1 \log_2 \frac{0.1}{0.1} $$

Variaton of Information¶

This measures how different two distributions are. It’s based on mutual information but tells us what information is lost or gained when switching between them.
(Total uncertainty left when switching between $X$ and $Y$)

Example (Clustering Differences):

  • Suppose you cluster customers based on spending habits.
  • If two algorithms give very different clusters, VI is high.
  • If both algorithms give similar clusters, VI is low.

Use in Data Science:

  • Comparing clustering algorithms
  • Information loss in feature selection
$$VI(Y, \hat{Y}) = \Eta(Y) + \Eta(\hat{Y}) -2I(Y, \hat{Y})$$

This is the sum of two positive terms $$VI(Y, \hat{Y}) = [\Eta(Y) -I(Y,\hat{Y})] + [\Eta(\hat{Y})-I(Y,\hat{Y})] = \Eta(Y|\hat{Y}) + \Eta(\hat{Y}|Y)$$

Metric¶

(Distance Measures) A metric quantifies how different or similar two points or distributions are.

Common Metrics:

  • Euclidean distance (for continuous data)
  • Manhattan distance (for grid-based paths)
  • Hamming distance (for binary data)
  • Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence (for probability distributions)

Example:

  • In a recommender system, the metric determines how close two users’ preferences are.

Use in Data Science:

  • Clustering (k-means, hierarchical clustering)
  • Nearest neighbor algorithms (k-NN, content-based filtering)
  • Anomaly detection (distance from normal behavior)

ROC Curve¶

The ROC curve evaluates a classifier’s performance across different thresholds.

🔹 Axes:

  • X-axis: False Positive Rate (FPR)
  • Y-axis: True Positive Rate (TPR)

🔹 Key Metrics:

  • AUC (Area Under the Curve) → Higher AUC = Better classifier
  • Closer to top-left = Better model

🔹 Example:

  • A perfect classifier has an AUC of 1.0.
  • A random classifier (coin flip) has an AUC of 0.5.

Use in Data Science:

  • Evaluating classification models (logistic regression, SVMs, deep

Receiver Operating Characteristic curve (ROC curve)¶

Given a two-class classification problem ($\omega_1$ and $\omega_2$), we denote the Type I Error (error probability of the false positive) with $\alpha$, and let $\beta$ be the Type II Error (error probability of a false negative).

As we saw previously,

The total error is equal to $\alpha+\beta$.

The sensitivity or recall (True Positive Fraction TPF) is

$$ \frac{TP}{p}=1-\alpha$$

The FP-rate (False Positive Fraction FPF) is

$$ \frac{FP}{n} = \alpha = 1- \text{specifity}$$

where $TP$, $FP$, $FN$ and $TN$ are the True positive, false negative, false negative and true false, respectively. The number of true positive is denoted by $p$ and the number of true negative with $n$.

When we have a parametric classifier, by moving a parameter, we can obtain different values of $\alpha$ and $\beta$.

For example, we assume that there are points on the line, the positive class (blue) and the negative class (red). Our classifier is a threshold point, which classifies the points to its left as positive and the points to its right as negative.

We can move it from the minimum of class $\omega_1$ to the maximum of class $\omega_2$, but realistically the range is from the minimum of $\omega_2$ to the maximum of $\omega_1$. When

When the threshold is at the intersection of the two curves, the total error $(\alpha+\beta)$ is a minimum: choosing the threshold (i.e., decision point) at the intersection minimizes the (total) probability of error and is the optimal decision rule.

On either side of the intersection, we can reduce $\alpha$ by increasing the threshold or we can reduce $\beta$ by reducing the threshold, but the total error will be larger than at the intersection point.

TPR = Sensibility
FPR = 1 - Specificitfy

The AUC score¶

The ROC curve allows a visual analysis; if we want to reduce the curve to a single number we can do this by calculating the Area Under the Curve (AUC).

A classifier ideally has an AUC of 1 and AUC values of different classifiers can be compared to give us a general performance averaged over different loss conditions.

If the two distributions overlap a lot, the ROC line drops close to the diagonal and the area below it (the AUC) drops towards 0.5: A value of exactly 0.5 indicates that there is complete overlap, and a classifier using this feature will be no better than random choice at discriminating the classes.

If the two distributions are well separated, the ROC line rises and the AUC approaches 1.
